## Bug

In `packages/playground-ui/src/lib/file/contentTypeFromUrl.ts`, the `getFileContentType` function has an error-handling gap in its `catch` block.

When the outer `fetch()` call fails (e.g. network error, 4xx/5xx), the catch block attempts:

```typescript
catch {
  const urlObject = new URL(url);  // ← throws if url is invalid!
  ...
}
```

If `url` is not a valid absolute URL (e.g. a relative path like `/files/report.pdf`, or a malformed string), `new URL(url)` will throw a `TypeError: Invalid URL`, which **escapes the catch block entirely** and becomes an unhandled promise rejection.

## Repro

```typescript
await getFileContentType('/relative/path/to/file.pdf');
// → Unhandled TypeError: Failed to construct 'URL': Invalid URL
```

The playground UI renders file attachments from various sources, and relative URLs are a realistic input.

## Fix

Wrap the URL construction in a try-catch and return `undefined` as a safe fallback:

```typescript
catch {
  try {
    const urlObject = new URL(url);
    const pathname = urlObject.pathname;
    const extension = pathname.split('.').pop();
    if (!extension) return undefined;
    return EXTENSION_TO_MIME[extension.toLowerCase()];
  } catch {
    // url is not a valid absolute URL — fall back to extension from the raw string
    const extension = url.split('.').pop()?.split('?')[0];
    if (!extension) return undefined;
    return EXTENSION_TO_MIME[extension.toLowerCase()];
  }
}
```

