# `consumeAgentStream` silently drops tripwire chunks — channel users get no response when processors block

## Bug description

When a processor with `strategy: "block"` triggers a tripwire (e.g. `PromptInjectionDetector`, `ModerationProcessor`), channel users (Slack, Discord) receive **no response at all**. The block is logged server-side but the user sees silence.

## Root cause

`AgentChannels.consumeAgentStream()` in `packages/core/src/channels/agent-channels.ts` iterates `stream.fullStream` and handles these chunk types:
- `text-delta`, `reasoning-delta`, `file`, `step-finish`, `finish`, `tool-call`, `tool-result`, `tool-call-approval`

There is **no handler for `tripwire` chunks**. When a processor blocks:

1. Input processor throws `TripWire`
2. Agent catches it, creates a stream with a single `tripwire` chunk via `getModelOutputForTripwire()`
3. `consumeAgentStream` iterates the stream, skips the unrecognized chunk type
4. Stream ends cleanly — `stream.error` is not set
5. No text was buffered, nothing is posted to the channel
6. User sees silence

## Expected behavior

When a processor blocks a message, the channel user should receive a response indicating their message was blocked, e.g.:

> :shield: Your message was blocked by a safety check (prompt-injection-detector): [reason]

## Reproduction

1. Create an agent with a `PromptInjectionDetector` (strategy: `"block"`)
2. Attach a Slack/Discord channel adapter
3. Send a message that triggers the detector
4. Observe: server logs show `"Input processor tripwire triggered"`, but the channel user gets no response

## Suggested fix

Add a `tripwire` branch in the `consumeAgentStream` loop (around line 1160 in `agent-channels.ts`):

```typescript
if (chunk.type === "tripwire") {
  await flushText();
  const reason = chunk.payload?.reason || "Your message was blocked by a safety check.";
  const processorId = chunk.payload?.processorId;
  const display = processorId
    ? `\u{1F6E1}\uFE0F Blocked by ${processorId}: ${reason}`
    : `\u{1F6E1}\uFE0F ${reason}`;
  await sdkThread.post(display);
  continue;
}
```

If `retry` is true in the tripwire payload, the agent will retry internally — in that case the chunk should probably be skipped silently (the retry will produce a new response). Only non-retry tripwires need to post to the channel.

## Workaround

We currently wrap `strategy: "block"` processors to convert `TripWire` into a regular `Error` at the processor level. Regular errors propagate to `handleChatMessage`'s catch block, which posts to Slack:

```typescript
function surfaceTripwire<T extends InputProcessorOrWorkflow>(processor: T): T {
  const original = (processor as any).processInput?.bind(processor);
  if (!original) return processor;

  (processor as any).processInput = async (args: ProcessInputArgs) => {
    let result;
    try {
      result = await original(args);
    } catch (error: unknown) {
      if ((error as Error)?.constructor?.name === "TripWire") {
        throw new Error((error as Error).message);
      }
      throw error;
    }
    if (result && typeof result === "object" && "tripwire" in result) {
      const tw = (result as { tripwire: { reason?: string } }).tripwire;
      throw new Error(tw.reason || "Request blocked by safety processor");
    }
    return result;
  };

  return processor;
}
```

## Environment

- `@mastra/core` 1.24.x
- Channel adapter: `@chat-adapter/slack`
- Processors: `PromptInjectionDetector`, `ModerationProcessor` with `strategy: "block"`

## Related

- #10935 — tripwire display in UI integrations (Studio/CopilotKit/AgUI) — similar gap but for UI, not channels

## Describe the Bug

When using a Mastra Agent with Observational Memory enabled and Gemini 3 Flash Preview via `@ai-sdk/google-vertex`, multi-step conversations with parallel tool calls fail with Vertex AI's `thought_signature` validation error (400):

```
Unable to submit request because function call `query_data` in the 5. content block
is missing a `thought_signature`
```

Gemini streaming returns `thoughtSignature` only on the first parallel function call part (known behavior — see [n8n fix](https://github.com/n8n-io/n8n/commit/3dbca3e), [google/adk-python#3705](https://github.com/google/adk-python/issues/3705)). Without OM, the AI SDK's step loop keeps all parallel tool calls in one content block, so at least one has the signature and Vertex accepts the request. With OM, the `processInputStep` runs between steps and reconstructs the message list, splitting tool calls into separate assistant messages. Each becomes its own content block — those without `thoughtSignature` are rejected.

**Disabling Observational Memory eliminates the error entirely.** Same agent, same prompt, same model — no OM → completes successfully with text output.

## Steps To Reproduce

1. Set up env vars: `GOOGLE_VERTEX_PROJECT`, `GOOGLE_VERTEX_LOCATION`, `GOOGLE_VERTEX_CREDENTIALS_BASE64`, `DATABASE_URL` (PostgreSQL)
2. Install deps: `@mastra/core@1.23.0`, `@mastra/memory@1.14.0` (also fails on `1.15.0`), `@mastra/pg@1.8.5`, `@ai-sdk/google-vertex@4.0.95`, `ai@6.0.116`, `zod`
3. Run the reproduction script below — stderr will show the 400 error

```javascript
import { randomUUID } from "node:crypto"
import { createVertex } from "@ai-sdk/google-vertex"
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent"
import { Memory } from "@mastra/memory"
import { PgVector, PostgresStore } from "@mastra/pg"
import { tool } from "ai"
import { z } from "zod"

const PROJECT = process.env.GOOGLE_VERTEX_PROJECT
const LOCATION = process.env.GOOGLE_VERTEX_LOCATION
const CREDS_B64 = process.env.GOOGLE_VERTEX_CREDENTIALS_BASE64
const DB_URL = process.env.DATABASE_URL

const creds = JSON.parse(Buffer.from(CREDS_B64, "base64").toString("utf-8"))
const provider = createVertex({ project: PROJECT, location: LOCATION, googleAuthOptions: { credentials: creds } })
const MODEL = "gemini-3-flash-preview"

// Large tool results (~2000 tokens each) trigger OM observer between steps
function makeLargeResult(id) {
  return {
    id,
    total_rows: 30,
    data: Array.from({ length: 30 }, (_, i) => ({
      row_id: `${id}-row-${i}`,
      name: `Record ${id} item ${i} with detailed description and metadata`,
      status: i % 3 === 0 ? "active" : i % 3 === 1 ? "pending" : "inactive",
      amount: Math.floor(Math.random() * 10000),
      notes: `Detailed notes for item ${i} in record ${id}. Additional context to trigger observational memory buffering.`,
    })),
  }
}

const memory = new Memory({
  storage: new PostgresStore({ id: "s", connectionString: DB_URL, schemaName: "mastra_thought_sig_repro" }),
  vector: new PgVector({ id: "v", connectionString: DB_URL, schemaName: "mastra_thought_sig_repro" }),
  embedder: provider.textEmbeddingModel("text-embedding-005"),
  options: {
    observationalMemory: { enabled: true, model: provider(MODEL), scope: "thread" },
    semanticRecall: false,
    workingMemory: { enabled: false },
  },
})

let callCount = 0
const agent = new Agent({
  name: "repro",
  instructions: "Follow instructions precisely. Use the provided tools. Call tools in parallel when instructed.",
  model: provider(MODEL),
  tools: {
    query_data: tool({
      description: "Query data by ID. Returns a large dataset. Call in parallel when multiple IDs are needed.",
      parameters: z.object({ id: z.string().describe("The record ID to query"), _pad: z.string().optional() }),
      execute: async ({ id }) => {
        callCount++
        console.log(`  [tool] id=${id} (#${callCount})`)
        return makeLargeResult(id)
      },
    }),
  },
  memory,
})

// Multi-step: 1 call -> 2 calls -> 8 parallel calls
const stream = await agent.stream(
  [{ role: "user", content: `Follow these steps EXACTLY:
Step 1: Call query_data with id="index-001".
Step 2: Call query_data for BOTH "rec-A" and "rec-B".
Step 3: Call query_data for ALL IN PARALLEL: det-1, det-2, det-3, det-4, det-5, det-6, det-7, det-8
After all results, write a summary. Each step must wait for previous results.` }],
  {
    maxSteps: 15,
    memory: { thread: `repro-${randomUUID()}`, resource: "repro-resource" },
    providerOptions: { vertex: { thinkingConfig: { includeThoughts: true } } },
  },
)

let text = ""
for await (const chunk of stream.textStream) text += chunk
console.log(`\nDone: text=${text.length}ch, toolCalls=${callCount}`)
if (text.length === 0) console.log("text is empty -- check stderr for thought_signature error")
```

## Link to Minimal Reproducible Example

The script above is self-contained. Save as `repro.mjs` in a project with the listed dependencies installed, set env vars, and run `node repro.mjs`.

## Expected Behavior

The agent should complete all 11 tool calls and return a text summary. Disabling Observational Memory (removing the `memory` option) produces this expected behavior with the exact same configuration.

## Environment Information

```
@mastra/core: 1.23.0
@mastra/memory: 1.14.0 (also tested 1.15.0 -- same issue)
@mastra/pg: 1.8.5
@ai-sdk/google-vertex: 4.0.95
@ai-sdk/google: 3.0.53
ai: 6.0.116
Node.js: v24.14.1
OS: Linux (Manjaro)
LLM Provider: Google Vertex AI (gemini-3-flash-preview)
```

## Additional Context

- Gemini streaming returns `thoughtSignature` only on the first parallel function call -- known across SDKs
- Without OM: AI SDK keeps parallel calls in one content block -> partial signatures OK -> Vertex accepts
- With OM: `processInputStep` splits tool calls into individual messages -> individual content blocks -> blocks with zero signatures -> Vertex rejects (400)
- Observed 12 occurrences in production over 22 hours across 6 different agents, all with OM active

