## Root Cause Analysis

We traced the issue to how messages are stored and reconstructed during OM's `processInputStep`.

### What happens:

1. **Gemini streaming returns `thoughtSignature` only on the first parallel function call** — this is known behavior (documented across n8n, Google ADK, LiteLLM, etc.)

2. **Mastra core stores each streaming tool call as an individual message** in the MessageList (one `tool-invocation` per message)

3. **Without OM**, the AI SDK's internal step loop keeps all parallel tool calls grouped in memory, so they become one content block when sent to Vertex. At least one has the signature → Vertex accepts.

4. **With OM**, `processInputStep` runs between steps and reads from the MessageList (which has split messages). When `@ai-sdk/google`'s `convertToGoogleGenerativeAIMessages` processes these, each message becomes a separate `model` content block. Blocks containing only function calls without `thoughtSignature` are rejected by Vertex (400).

### Debug output showing the failing request:

```
[0] user:  text(490)
[1] model: thought(291) sig=false
[2] model: functionCall(query_data) sig=true     ← has signature, OK
[3] user:  functionResponse(query_data)
[4] model: functionCall(query_data) sig=false     ← alone in block, 0 sigs → REJECTED
[5] user:  functionResponse(query_data)
[6] model: functionCall x6, all sig=false         ← 6 calls, 0 sigs → would also be rejected
[7] user:  functionResponse x6
```

Vertex validates per content block: if ALL function calls in a model block lack `thoughtSignature`, it returns 400. A block with at least one signature passes.

## Workaround

We applied a pnpm patch to `@mastra/memory@1.14.0` that propagates the last known `thoughtSignature` to tool-invocation parts that are missing it, at the end of `processInputStep`:

```javascript
// At the end of processInputStep, before `return messageList`:
try {
  var _allMsgs = messageList.get.all.db();
  var _lastSig = void 0;
  // First pass: find the last known thoughtSignature
  for (var _mi = 0; _mi < _allMsgs.length; _mi++) {
    var _msg = _allMsgs[_mi];
    if (!_msg || !_msg.content || !_msg.content.parts) continue;
    for (var _pi = 0; _pi < _msg.content.parts.length; _pi++) {
      var _part = _msg.content.parts[_pi];
      if (!_part || !_part.providerMetadata) continue;
      var _vtx = _part.providerMetadata.vertex || _part.providerMetadata.google;
      if (_vtx && _vtx.thoughtSignature) {
        _lastSig = _vtx.thoughtSignature;
      }
    }
  }
  // Second pass: propagate to tool-invocation parts missing it
  if (_lastSig) {
    for (var _mi2 = 0; _mi2 < _allMsgs.length; _mi2++) {
      var _msg2 = _allMsgs[_mi2];
      if (!_msg2 || !_msg2.content || !_msg2.content.parts) continue;
      for (var _pi2 = 0; _pi2 < _msg2.content.parts.length; _pi2++) {
        var _part2 = _msg2.content.parts[_pi2];
        if (!_part2 || _part2.type !== "tool-invocation") continue;
        if (!_part2.providerMetadata) _part2.providerMetadata = {};
        var _hasVtx = _part2.providerMetadata.vertex && _part2.providerMetadata.vertex.thoughtSignature;
        var _hasGoogle = _part2.providerMetadata.google && _part2.providerMetadata.google.thoughtSignature;
        if (!_hasVtx && !_hasGoogle) {
          if (!_part2.providerMetadata.vertex) _part2.providerMetadata.vertex = {};
          _part2.providerMetadata.vertex.thoughtSignature = _lastSig;
        }
      }
    }
  }
} catch (_e) {}
```

This ensures every tool-invocation part has a `thoughtSignature` before the AI SDK converts them to Vertex API content blocks, regardless of how OM splits the messages.

## Patch file

Attach the patch file below to apply via pnpm:

1. Save as `patches/@mastra__memory@1.14.0.patch`
2. Add to `pnpm-workspace.yaml`:
```yaml
patchedDependencies:
  '@mastra/memory@1.14.0': patches/@mastra__memory@1.14.0.patch
```
3. Run `pnpm install`

<details>
<summary>patches/@mastra__memory@1.14.0.patch</summary>

```diff
diff --git a/dist/chunk-GXDPND6K.js b/dist/chunk-GXDPND6K.js
index 75b449086c679ad96e0a92af3741c2d5d2802d59..91c67047c1ae75278bcc9493f7479bbad4d9fa4a 100644
--- a/dist/chunk-GXDPND6K.js
+++ b/dist/chunk-GXDPND6K.js
@@ -8595,6 +8595,45 @@ var ObservationalMemoryProcessor = class {
           });
         }
       }
+      // [PATCH] Propagate thoughtSignature across tool-invocation parts.
+      // Gemini streaming only includes thoughtSignature on the first parallel
+      // function call. OM splits tool calls into individual messages, which
+      // become separate content blocks. Vertex rejects blocks where ALL
+      // function calls lack a signature. Propagate the last known signature
+      // to parts that are missing it.
+      try {
+        var _allMsgs = messageList.get.all.db();
+        var _lastSig = void 0;
+        for (var _mi = 0; _mi < _allMsgs.length; _mi++) {
+          var _msg = _allMsgs[_mi];
+          if (!_msg || !_msg.content || !_msg.content.parts) continue;
+          for (var _pi = 0; _pi < _msg.content.parts.length; _pi++) {
+            var _part = _msg.content.parts[_pi];
+            if (!_part || !_part.providerMetadata) continue;
+            var _vtx = _part.providerMetadata.vertex || _part.providerMetadata.google;
+            if (_vtx && _vtx.thoughtSignature) {
+              _lastSig = _vtx.thoughtSignature;
+            }
+          }
+        }
+        if (_lastSig) {
+          for (var _mi2 = 0; _mi2 < _allMsgs.length; _mi2++) {
+            var _msg2 = _allMsgs[_mi2];
+            if (!_msg2 || !_msg2.content || !_msg2.content.parts) continue;
+            for (var _pi2 = 0; _pi2 < _msg2.content.parts.length; _pi2++) {
+              var _part2 = _msg2.content.parts[_pi2];
+              if (!_part2 || _part2.type !== "tool-invocation") continue;
+              if (!_part2.providerMetadata) _part2.providerMetadata = {};
+              var _hasVtx = _part2.providerMetadata.vertex && _part2.providerMetadata.vertex.thoughtSignature;
+              var _hasGoogle = _part2.providerMetadata.google && _part2.providerMetadata.google.thoughtSignature;
+              if (!_hasVtx && !_hasGoogle) {
+                if (!_part2.providerMetadata.vertex) _part2.providerMetadata.vertex = {};
+                _part2.providerMetadata.vertex.thoughtSignature = _lastSig;
+              }
+            }
+          }
+        }
+      } catch (_e) {}
       return messageList;
     });
   }
```

</details>

body:
### Problem Statement

Mastra has 9 auth providers (Auth0, Clerk, Firebase, Okta, Supabase, WorkOS, etc.) — all designed for **human users** authenticating via browser sessions, OAuth flows, or human-issued JWTs. None address **agent-to-agent authentication**: an autonomous agent calling your Mastra-powered API, proving its identity, and being authorized based on behavioral trust rather than static credentials.

As agentic architectures become production-critical, the auth model shifts. An agent calling your API doesn't have a browser session or an OAuth redirect URI. It presents a cryptographically signed token asserting its identity, issued by an agent identity provider. The question isn't "which human authorized this request?" — it's "which agent is this, and should I trust it?"

Today, there's no way to express this in Mastra's auth system without building it from scratch.

### Proposed Solution

Add `@mastra/auth-agentlair` — an auth provider that verifies agent identity tokens issued by [AgentLair](https://agentlair.dev), following the same pattern as `@mastra/auth-auth0`.

AgentLair issues EdDSA-signed JWTs (Agent Authentication Tokens) verifiable via a standard JWKS endpoint at `https://agentlair.dev/.well-known/jwks.json`. The `@mastra/auth` package already exports `verifyJwks()`, and existing providers (Auth0, WorkOS) already use `jose`'s `createRemoteJWKSet` + `jwtVerify` — the same pattern works here.

**Auth provider (~50 lines):**

```typescript
import { MastraAuthProvider, type MastraAuthProviderOptions } from '@mastra/auth';
import { createRemoteJWKSet, jwtVerify, type JWTPayload } from 'jose';

export interface AgentLairUser {
  agentId: string;
  iss: string;
  trustScore?: number;  // 0-1000, from AgentLair behavioral trust API
}

export interface AgentLairAuthOptions extends MastraAuthProviderOptions<AgentLairUser> {
  jwksUrl?: string;           // Default: https://agentlair.dev/.well-known/jwks.json
  issuer?: string;            // Expected issuer claim
  requiredTrustScore?: number; // Minimum behavioral trust score (0-1000)
}

export class MastraAuthAgentLair extends MastraAuthProvider<AgentLairUser> {
  private jwks: ReturnType<typeof createRemoteJWKSet>;
  private issuer?: string;
  private requiredTrustScore: number;

  constructor(options: AgentLairAuthOptions = {}) {
    super({ name: 'agentlair', ...options });
    this.jwks = createRemoteJWKSet(
      new URL(options.jwksUrl ?? 'https://agentlair.dev/.well-known/jwks.json')
    );
    this.issuer = options.issuer;
    this.requiredTrustScore = options.requiredTrustScore ?? 0;
  }

  async authenticateToken(token: string): Promise<AgentLairUser | null> {
    try {
      const { payload } = await jwtVerify(token, this.jwks, {
        issuer: this.issuer,
        algorithms: ['EdDSA'],
      });
      return {
        agentId: payload.sub!,
        iss: payload.iss!,
        trustScore: (payload as any).trust_score,
      };
    } catch {
      return null;
    }
  }

  async authorizeUser(user: AgentLairUser): Promise<boolean> {
    if (this.requiredTrustScore > 0 && (user.trustScore ?? 0) < this.requiredTrustScore) {
      return false;
    }
    return true;
  }
}
```

**Configuration:**

```typescript
const mastra = new Mastra({
  server: {
    auth: new MastraAuthAgentLair({
      requiredTrustScore: 500, // Only trust agents with score >= 500
    }),
  },
});
```

**Optional RBAC provider** — maps behavioral trust tiers to Mastra roles:

```typescript
export class MastraRBACAgentLair implements IRBACProvider<AgentLairUser> {
  constructor(private config: {
    tierMapping: Record<string, { minScore: number; permissions: string[] }>;
  }) {}

  async getRoles(user: AgentLairUser): Promise<string[]> {
    const score = user.trustScore ?? 0;
    return Object.entries(this.config.tierMapping)
      .filter(([_, tier]) => score >= tier.minScore)
      .map(([role]) => role);
  }
  // ... hasRole, getPermissions, etc.
}
```

This enables trust-tiered agent access:

```typescript
server: {
  auth: new MastraAuthAgentLair(),
  rbac: new MastraRBACAgentLair({
    tierMapping: {
      'agent:untrusted': { minScore: 0, permissions: ['agents:read'] },
      'agent:verified':  { minScore: 500, permissions: ['agents:read', 'agents:execute'] },
      'agent:trusted':   { minScore: 800, permissions: ['agents:*', 'workflows:*', 'memory:read'] },
    },
  }),
}
```

### Component

Integrations, Agents

### Alternatives Considered

- **API keys / static tokens**: No identity semantics. Can't revoke per-agent, can't differentiate trust levels. Doesn't answer "who is this agent?"
- **Reusing a human auth provider (Auth0/Clerk) for agents**: Technically works for token verification, but the user model is wrong — agents don't have emails, profiles, or org memberships. Trust is behavioral, not declarative.
- **External middleware**: Possible today, but auth providers exist precisely to avoid this. Mastra's `MastraAuthProvider` abstraction handles token verification, user resolution, and route protection in one place.

### Example Use Case

Multi-agent system where external agents consume your Mastra-powered API:

1. **Agent marketplace**: You expose agents via Mastra. Third-party agents call your API. You need to verify their identity and authorize based on behavioral reputation, not just a shared API key.
2. **Cross-org agent orchestration**: Your company's agents call a partner's Mastra deployment. Both sides verify agent identity via AgentLair's JWKS, with trust scores gating access to sensitive workflows.
3. **Trust-gated tool access**: An agent with a low trust score can read agent metadata, but only agents with verified behavioral history (score > 800) can execute workflows or write to memory.

### Additional Context

- **Technical fit is strong**: The Auth0 provider is the closest analog — pure JWKS verification, no session management. AgentLair uses EdDSA (OKP/Ed25519) instead of RSA, but `jose` handles both transparently.
- **Package structure**: Would follow the existing `auth/{provider}/` scaffold with `@mastra/auth-agentlair` package name.
- **Category precedent**: [OpenBox](https://openbox.so) recently shipped a governance integration for agent oversight — agent trust/identity is an emerging provider category alongside human auth.
- AgentLair docs: [agentlair.dev](https://agentlair.dev)

### Verification

- [x] I have searched the existing issues to make sure this is not a duplicate
- [x] I have provided sufficient context for the team to understand the request

## Environment

- `@mastra/core`: 1.24.0
- `@ai-sdk/anthropic`: 3.0.64
- `ai`: 6.0.140
- Model: `claude-sonnet-4-6` via `anthropic()` from `@ai-sdk/anthropic`

## Description

Custom tools called programmatically from inside `code_execution` always receive `{}` as input, regardless of what arguments Claude passes.

Claude writes correct Python inside the sandbox:

```python
result = await my_tool({"queries": ["SELECT 1 as test"]})
```

The tool's `execute` function gets `{}`:

```
Tool input validation failed for my-tool.
- queries: Invalid input: expected array, received undefined
Provided arguments: {}
```

Every PTC invocation fails this way. The agent burns through its step budget retrying different call patterns — none work because the input is stripped before it reaches the tool.

## Reproduction

```typescript
import { anthropic } from '@ai-sdk/anthropic';
import { Agent } from '@mastra/core/agent';
import { createTool } from '@mastra/core/tools';
import { z } from 'zod';

const myTool = createTool({
  id: 'my-tool',
  description: 'A tool that takes a query parameter',
  providerOptions: {
    anthropic: {
      allowedCallers: ['code_execution_20260120'],
    },
  },
  inputSchema: z.object({
    query: z.string(),
  }),
  execute: async ({ query }) => {
    return { result: query };
  },
});

const agent = new Agent({
  id: 'test-agent',
  model: anthropic('claude-sonnet-4-6'), // must use direct provider, not string — see note below
  tools: {
    code_execution: anthropic.tools.codeExecution_20260120(),
    [myTool.id]: myTool,
  },
  defaultOptions: { maxSteps: 10 },
});
```

Ask the agent anything that triggers a tool call from code execution. The tool will always receive `{}`.

**Side note:** string-based model configs (e.g. `'anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6'`) cause `ModelRouterLanguageModel` to drop `code_execution_20260120` as an unsupported provider tool. You have to use `anthropic('claude-sonnet-4-6')` directly. That might be worth a separate issue.

## Root cause

I traced this through the chunk conversion pipeline in `packages/core/src/stream/base/output.ts`.

### What `@ai-sdk/anthropic` emits for a PTC tool call

1. `tool-input-start` — `{ id, toolName }` (no `providerExecuted` flag)
2. `tool-input-delta` — `{ id, delta: '{"queries":["SELECT 1"]}' }` (full input as one delta)
3. `tool-input-end` — `{ id }`
4. `tool-call` — `{ toolCallId, toolName, input: '{"queries":["SELECT 1"]}', providerMetadata: { anthropic: { caller: ... } } }`

### Where Mastra drops the input

`convertFullStreamChunkToMastra` converts these AI SDK events into Mastra's internal format. The streaming accumulation code in `output.ts` works like this:

1. `tool-call-input-streaming-start` stores metadata in `toolCallStreamingMeta[id]`
2. `tool-call-delta` should push to `toolCallArgsDeltas[id]`
3. `tool-call-input-streaming-end` builds a synthetic `tool-call` from the accumulated deltas

The synthetic ends up with `args: {}` — the deltas aren't accumulating. Either the `tool-input-delta` → `tool-call-delta` conversion silently drops the value, or `toolCallArgsDeltas[id]` never gets initialized for PTC calls. I wasn't able to narrow it further without stepping through at runtime.

Then comes the second problem. When the real `tool-call` event arrives (which *does* carry the full input), it finds the existing synthetic and bails:

```javascript
case "tool-call": {
  const existingSynthetic = self.#toolCalls.find(
    (tc) => tc.payload.toolCallId === chunk.payload.toolCallId
  );
  if (existingSynthetic) {
    // merges providerMetadata and dynamic — but NOT args
    return; // ← full input from the real tool-call is discarded
  }
}
```

So the tool runs with the synthetic's empty `args: {}`.

## Expected vs actual

**Expected:** Tool receives `{"queries": ["SELECT 1 as test"]}`

**Actual:** Tool receives `{}`

## Possible fixes

**Option A** (quick): When the `tool-call` handler finds an existing synthetic with empty args, merge the real tool-call's args into it:

```javascript
if (existingSynthetic) {
  if (Object.keys(existingSynthetic.payload.args).length === 0 && chunk.payload.args) {
    existingSynthetic.payload.args = chunk.payload.args;
  }
  // ... existing metadata merging
  return;
}
```

**Option B** (proper): Fix the delta accumulation so the synthetic gets built with the right args in the first place. Needs investigation into why `tool-input-delta` events aren't being picked up for PTC calls.

