## Verified fix with a local patch

I patched `@mastra/core@1.24.0` locally and confirmed this resolves the empty input issue. Here's the patch.

### The patch

```diff
--- a/node_modules/@mastra/core/dist/chunk-SE7ST47S.js
+++ b/node_modules/@mastra/core/dist/chunk-SE7ST47S.js
@@ -3033,6 +3033,9 @@ var MastraModelOutput = class extends MastraBase {
             case "tool-call": {
               const existingSynthetic = self.#toolCalls.find((tc) => tc.payload.toolCallId === chunk.payload.toolCallId);
               if (existingSynthetic) {
+                if (chunk.payload.args && Object.keys(existingSynthetic.payload.args || {}).length === 0) {
+                  existingSynthetic.payload.args = chunk.payload.args;
+                }
                 if (chunk.payload.providerMetadata && !existingSynthetic.payload.providerMetadata) {
                   existingSynthetic.payload.providerMetadata = chunk.payload.providerMetadata;
                 }
```

Same change applied to `chunk-V7H57YBW.cjs` (the CJS build).

### Why this works

When the `tool-call-input-streaming-end` handler creates a synthetic tool-call chunk, the accumulated deltas produce `args: {}` for PTC calls. The real `tool-call` event that follows *does* carry the full input in `chunk.payload.args`, but the existing merge logic only copies `providerMetadata` and `dynamic` — not `args`.

The patch adds one check: if the synthetic's args are empty and the real tool-call has args, merge them in.

Hey @Rul1an — yes, individual score records from observability are the right seam for an external evidence consumer with this use case.

To make this concrete: Mastra's observability layer has a pluggable **exporter interface** (`ObservabilityExporter`) that receives typed events — including dedicated **`ScoreEvent`** signals. You could write a minimal custom exporter that *only* handles score events and ignores everything else (traces, logs, metrics).

The `ScoreEvent` contains an `ExportedScore` with exactly the kind of bounded shape you described:

- `scorerId` / `scorerName` — scorer identifier
- `score` — numeric value
- `reason` — optional explanation
- `timestamp` — when the score was recorded
- `traceId` / `spanId` — optional target anchors
- `targetEntityType` — what was scored
- `scorerVersion`, `scoreSource`, `metadata` — optional extras

A minimal exporter would look something like:

```typescript
import { BaseExporter } from '@mastra/observability';
import type { ScoreEvent, TracingEvent } from '@mastra/core/observability';

class AssayScoreExporter extends BaseExporter {
  name = 'assay-score-exporter';

  async onScoreEvent(event: ScoreEvent): Promise<void> {
    const { scorerId, scorerName, score, reason, timestamp, traceId, targetEntityType } = event.score;
    // Forward to Assay however you want
  }

  // Required by interface, but can be a no-op if you only care about scores
  async exportTracingEvent(_event: TracingEvent): Promise<void> {}
}
```

Then wire it up:

```typescript
import { Observability } from '@mastra/observability';

new Mastra({
  observability: new Observability({
    configs: {
      default: {
        serviceName: 'my-app',
        exporters: [new AssayScoreExporter()],
      },
    },
  }),
});
```

The event bus routes `ScoreEvent`s only to exporters that implement `onScoreEvent`, so you get exactly the signal type you want without inheriting traces, dashboard semantics, or runtime concerns. The `ExportedScore` shape is intentionally the thinnest score-result surface we expose — it's closer to your target than the scorer definitions or experiment-item results.

For your sample, rebuilding around a real score record from this exporter interface would give you a stable, minimal integration point.

@Rul1an I see in your document mention of `exporter.addScoreToTrace(...)`

Note that this is the old pathway for sending score data and it will be deprecated soon.

The `ScoreEvent` is the new path.  Additionally the `ExportedScore` object inside the event will soon be gaining a few extra fields.  The most important for y'all might be the `ScoreId`; a uuid linking the specific score back to the mastra system.

