### Describe the Bug

This might not be a Mastra issue, I am still logging it here since I expect many of your users to use `@hono/zod-openapi` and it might therefore be interesting to you.

#### 1. `createStep` — `inputData` not inferred from `inputSchema`

When `@hono/zod-openapi` is imported, `inputData` in the `execute` callback is no longer inferred from the `inputSchema`. It falls back to a wider type instead of the expected `{ prompt: string }`.

```ts
import {} from "@hono/zod-openapi"; // triggers the bug

const step = createStep({
  id: "my-step",
  inputSchema: z.object({ prompt: z.string() }),
  outputSchema: z.object({ text: z.string() }),
  execute: async ({ inputData }) => {
    // BUG: inputData is not typed as { prompt: string }
    return { text: "test" };
  },
});
```

#### 2. `createWorkflow` / `workflow.then()` — incompatible steps silently accepted

A step requiring `{ prompt: string, extra: number }` can be chained onto a workflow whose `inputSchema` only provides `{ prompt: string }`. No type error is raised.

```ts
import {} from "@hono/zod-openapi";

const step = createStep({
  id: "needs-extra",
  inputSchema: z.object({ prompt: z.string(), extra: z.number() }),
  outputSchema: z.object({ text: z.string() }),
  execute: async ({ inputData }) => ({
    text: `${inputData.prompt}:${inputData.extra}`,
  }),
});

const workflow = createWorkflow({
  id: "only-provides-prompt",
  inputSchema: z.object({ prompt: z.string() }),
  outputSchema: z.object({ text: z.string() }),
});

workflow.then(step); // BUG: should be a type error
```

#### 3. `createTool` — `requestContextSchema` not enforced

When a `requestContextSchema` is defined, `execute` should require a matching `requestContext` argument. Instead, an empty object `{}` is accepted without error.

```ts
import {} from "@hono/zod-openapi";

const tool = createTool({
  id: "my-tool",
  description: "Tool with required context",
  requestContextSchema: z.object({ patientId: z.string() }),
  execute: async () => ({ ok: true }),
});

tool.execute?.({}, {}); // BUG: should require { requestContext: { patientId: string } }
```

### Key observation

Removing the `import {} from "@hono/zod-openapi"` line from any of these files restores correct type inference. The import has no runtime effect — it only loads types that interfere with Mastra's Zod-based generics.

### Steps To Reproduce

  Minimal repro: https://github.com/abrahamcl/mastra-type-inference-bug                                   

  git clone https://github.com/abrahamcl/mastra-type-inference-bug                                         
  cd mastra-bug                                                                                
  pnpm install
  pnpm test      

### Link to Minimal Reproducible Example

https://github.com/abrahamcl/mastra-type-inference-bug 

### Expected Behavior

  All three APIs should maintain full type inference regardless of what other packages are     
  loaded in the TypeScript program. Specifically:

  1. createStep inputData should be inferred as the z.infer of inputSchema                     
  2. workflow.then() should reject steps whose inputSchema is not satisfied by the preceding
  output                                                                                       
  3. createTool should require requestContext matching requestContextSchema when defined

### Environment Information

```block
Not related to inference or browsers. This is purely a type level issue
```

### Verification

- [x] I have searched the existing issues to make sure this is not a duplicate
- [x] I have included sufficient information for the team to reproduce and understand the issue

