### Describe the Bug

`startAsyncBufferedObservation` in `ObservationalMemory` stores a detached promise (asyncOp) in a static Map with .finally() but no .catch(). If the underlying storage call fails, the promise rejects without a handler, producing an unhandled promise rejection.

The bug is masked during multi-step agent execution because a subsequent `runAsyncBufferedObservation` call accidentally catches the previous rejection via `try { await existingOp } catch {}`. However, when the failing `asyncOp` is the last one, meaning no future step creates a new `runAsyncBufferedObservation` to consume it, the rejection is unhandled.

## When the bug manifests
The rejection goes unhandled whenever the rejected `asyncOp` is the last one for that buffer key.

```
startAsyncBufferedObservation(record, threadId, ...) {
    // ...
    const asyncOp = this.runAsyncBufferedObservation(
      record, threadId, unobservedMessages, bufferKey, writer, requestContext
    ).finally(() => {
      ObservationalMemory.asyncBufferingOps.delete(bufferKey);
      unregisterOp(record.id, 'bufferingObservation');
      // ...
    });
    ObservationalMemory.asyncBufferingOps.set(bufferKey, asyncOp);  // ❌ no .catch()
}
```

The promise is stored but never has a `.catch()` attached.

Inside `runAsyncBufferedObservation`, the `persistMessages` call sits outside the try/catch block:

```
async runAsyncBufferedObservation(...) {
    const existingOp = ObservationalMemory.asyncBufferingOps.get(bufferKey);
    if (existingOp) {
      try {
        await existingOp;    // ← accidentally catches PREVIOUS asyncOp's rejection
      } catch {}              //   (mutex-wait pattern, not intentional error handling)
    }
    // ...

    // ❌ UNPROTECTED — no try/catch
    await this.messageHistory.persistMessages({ messages, threadId, resourceId });

    try {
      // ✅ This IS protected
      await this.doAsyncBufferedObservation(...);
    } catch (error) {
      // handles failure markers, logs with omError
    }
}
```

## Why it's masked during normal multi-step execution
The `try { await existingOp } catch {}` at the top of runAsyncBufferedObservation waits for the previous buffering op to finish before starting a new one. As a side effect, it catches any rejection from the previous `asyncOp`. So during a multi-step agent run where step N+1 triggers another startAsyncBufferedObservation, the rejection from step N is consumed. But when the failing op is the last one, no subsequent call exists to catch it.

### Steps To Reproduce

Described here: https://github.com/trevor-zablocki-anrok/mastra/tree/unhandled-persist-messages-promise

### Link to Minimal Reproducible Example

https://github.com/trevor-zablocki-anrok/mastra/tree/unhandled-persist-messages-promise

### Expected Behavior

I would expect failures to persist messages would be caught and logged, then runAsyncBufferedObservation would return.

