### Describe the Bug

When a tool has no `execute` function (client-side tool), AI SDK's inner do-while loop correctly stops and returns `reason="tool-calls"`. However, Mastra's outer dowhile loop treats `reason="tool-calls"` as `isContinued=true` and continues calling the model — even though the tool was intentionally left without `execute` for client-side execution.

This causes the model to be called again **without any `tool_result`** in context, leading it to generate the **exact same tool call** repeatedly within a single stream. The client then receives multiple duplicate tool calls.

### Root Cause (source-level trace)

**AI SDK inner loop** (correct behavior):
```javascript
// ai/dist/index.mjs
// tool.execute == null → returns undefined → filtered out
// do-while condition: clientToolOutputs.length(0) !== clientToolCalls.length(1)
// → FALSE → inner loop stops → step finishes with reason="tool-calls"
```

**Mastra outer loop** (incorrect behavior):
```javascript
// @mastra/core dist/chunk-VBPU6CLZ.js L12119
isContinued: !["stop", "error"].includes(chunk.payload.stepResult.reason)
// reason="tool-calls" → isContinued=true → dowhile continues

// L13776: dowhile condition
return typedInputData.stepResult?.isContinued ?? false;
// → true → calls model again
```

**`listClientTools()` strips execute but dowhile ignores it:**
```javascript
// L20314: execute is explicitly destructured away
const { execute: execute2, ...rest } = tool2;
// But the dowhile loop at L13776 never checks if the tool was a client tool
```

### Reproduction

1. Define a tool with `createTool()` — no `execute` function
2. Pass it to an agent (either as a regular tool or via `clientTools`)
3. Call `agent.stream()` with `maxSteps > 1`
4. Model generates a tool call for the no-execute tool
5. **Expected**: Stream ends after one tool call, `finishReason="tool-calls"`, control returns to client
6. **Actual**: Mastra's dowhile calls the model again (without tool_result), model generates the same tool call, loop continues until `maxSteps` or `onIterationComplete` stops it

### Evidence from eval

Using the same agent + same tool + same prompt:

| Path | dispatch has execute? | Duplicate tool calls? |
|------|----------------------|----------------------|
| `MASTRA_DEV=true` (execute injected at runtime) | Yes | **0 duplicates** (3/3 runs) |
| Production backend (no execute, client tool) | No | **100% duplicate** (every run) |

The **only** difference is whether the tool has `execute`. When it does, AI SDK's inner loop completes normally, `reason="stop"`, and Mastra's dowhile exits. When it doesn't, the chain described above causes repeated model calls.

### Expected Behavior

When all tool calls in a step are for tools without `execute` (client tools), Mastra's dowhile should set `isContinued=false` and stop — matching AI SDK's design intent that "a tool without execute stops the loop" ([AI SDK docs](https://ai-sdk.dev/docs/agents/loop-control)).

### Suggested Fix

In the dowhile condition callback, check if the step's reason is `"tool-calls"` AND all called tools lack `execute` (or are marked as `"client-tool"` via `listClientTools`). If so, set `isContinued = false`.

Pseudocode:
```javascript
// In the dowhile condition (around L13776):
if (stepResult.reason === "tool-calls") {
  const allClientTools = stepResult.toolCalls?.every(
    tc => resolvedTools[tc.toolName]?.logType === "client-tool" || !resolvedTools[tc.toolName]?.execute
  );
  if (allClientTools) {
    stepResult.isContinued = false;
  }
}
```

### Related Issues

- #2728 — client-side tool execution feature request
- #12405 — tool call args lost when split across messages (client tools)
- #12683 — messages duplicated when using `addToolOutput` with client tools
- #8830 — repeated messages with useChat integration

### Environment Information

```
@mastra/core: 1.8.0 (also confirmed on 1.10.0)
ai (AI SDK): v5 (@ai-sdk/provider-v5)
Node.js: v22
```

### Verification

- [x] I have searched the existing issues to make sure this is not a duplicate
- [x] I have included sufficient information for the team to reproduce and understand the issue

## Summary

We've identified several interrelated bugs in Working Memory that affect data integrity, initialization, and token efficiency. We're currently using pnpm patches against `@mastra/core@1.10.0` and `@mastra/memory@1.6.1` to work around these issues.

---

## Issues

### 1. `generateEmptyFromSchema` fails on string schemas, nested objects, and default values

**Location:** `WorkingMemory.generateEmptyFromSchema()` in `@mastra/core`

**Problem:** The method doesn't handle:
- String-type schema input (needs `JSON.parse` first)
- Nested objects with `properties` (only handles flat structures)
- `default` values defined in the schema

**Current behavior:**
```js
// String schema → crash or returns null
// Nested object → gets empty string instead of recursive processing
// Schema with defaults → ignored
```

**Suggested fix:**
```js
generateEmptyFromSchema(schema) {
  try {
    const parsedSchema = typeof schema === 'string' ? JSON.parse(schema) : schema;
    if (!parsedSchema || parsedSchema.type !== "object" || !parsedSchema.properties) return {};

    const TYPE_DEFAULTS = {
      string: "", array: [], number: 0, integer: 0, boolean: false
    };

    const processProperty = (prop) => {
      if (prop.type === "object" && prop.properties) {
        return processProperties(prop.properties);
      }
      if (prop.default !== undefined) return prop.default;
      return TYPE_DEFAULTS[prop.type] ?? "";
    };

    const processProperties = (properties) => {
      const obj = {};
      for (const [key, prop] of Object.entries(properties)) {
        obj[key] = processProperty(prop);
      }
      return obj;
    };

    return processProperties(parsedSchema.properties);
  } catch {
    return {};
  }
}
```

---

### 2. Thread metadata is overwritten instead of merged

**Location:** `AgentLegacyHandler` and `createPrepareMemoryStep` in `@mastra/core`

**Problem:** When updating thread metadata, the existing metadata is completely replaced instead of merged:

```js
// Current (breaks existing metadata fields)
thread: { ...existingThread, metadata: thread.metadata }

// Expected (preserves existing fields)
thread: { ...existingThread, metadata: { ...existingThread.metadata, ...thread.metadata } }
```

**Impact:** Any metadata fields not included in the update are silently lost.

---

### 3. Working Memory does not support partial JSON updates (full overwrite)

**Location:** `updateWorkingMemory` tool execute in `@mastra/core` (MockMemory) and `@mastra/memory`

**Problem:** When the LLM sends a partial JSON update (only changed fields), the entire working memory is replaced. This causes data loss for unchanged fields and wastes tokens by forcing the LLM to re-send the complete JSON every time.

**Suggested fix:** Add shallow merge for JSON-format working memory:

```js
// In updateWorkingMemory execute:
let inputMemory = typeof inputData.memory === "string" 
  ? inputData.memory : JSON.stringify(inputData.memory);

try {
  const parsed = JSON.parse(inputMemory);
  if (parsed && typeof parsed === "object" && !Array.isArray(parsed)) {
    const existingWM = await memory.getWorkingMemory({ threadId, resourceId, memoryConfig });
    if (existingWM) {
      try {
        const existingParsed = JSON.parse(existingWM);
        if (existingParsed && typeof existingParsed === "object" && !Array.isArray(existingParsed)) {
          inputMemory = JSON.stringify({ ...existingParsed, ...parsed });
        }
      } catch {}
    }
  }
} catch {}
```

Also update the tool description to reflect partial update semantics:
```
"Update the working memory. For JSON format, you can send only the fields 
that changed (partial update). Unchanged fields will be preserved automatically."
```

---

### 4. `<working_memory_data>` is empty when no data exists yet (initial template not shown)

**Location:** `getWorkingMemoryToolInstruction()` in `@mastra/core`

**Problem:** When `data` is `null`/`undefined` (first interaction), the `<working_memory_data>` section is empty. The LLM has no reference for the expected structure, making the first `updateWorkingMemory` call unreliable.

**Suggested fix:**
```js
const displayData = data || (hasEmptyWorkingMemoryTemplateObject 
  ? JSON.stringify(emptyWorkingMemoryTemplateObject, null, 2) 
  : null);

// Then use displayData instead of data in the template:
// <working_memory_data>
// ${displayData}
// </working_memory_data>
```

---

### 5. `updateWorkingMemory` tool description instructs LLM to send entire content (token waste)

**Location:** `getWorkingMemoryToolInstruction()` in `@mastra/core`

**Problem:** The instruction says:
> "REMEMBER: the way you update your working memory is by calling the updateWorkingMemory tool with the **entire** JSON content."

This forces the LLM to re-send the complete working memory on every update, even when only one field changed. Combined with issue #3 (no partial merge), this wastes significant tokens.

**Suggested fix** (after implementing #3):
```
- IMPORTANT: For JSON format, you can send only the fields that changed 
  (partial update) - they will be merged with existing data.
```

---

## Affected Versions

- `@mastra/core`: confirmed in 1.0.4 and 1.10.0
- `@mastra/memory`: confirmed in 1.0.0 and 1.6.1


## Environment

- `@mastra/core`: 1.10.0
- `@mastra/memory`: 1.6.1
- PostgreSQL: 16.x
- Node.js: 22.x

