### Problem Statement

Since the v1 upgrade, PATCH /memory/threads/:threadId validates that the request's resourceId matches the thread's current resourceId and prevents reassignment (introduced in PR #[12251](https://github.com/mastra-ai/mastra/pull/12251), commit bb68d4d). We understand this is an intentional security measure for multi-tenant isolation. Attempting to update the resourceId using thread.update was no longer possible after this upgrade due to `validateThreadOwnership` check that is now happening.




### Proposed Solution

- Is POST /memory/threads likely to receive the same validateThreadOwnership check in future? If so, our workaround would break. We'd like to plan accordingly.
- Would you consider adding a first-class API for thread ownership transfer? For example, a POST /memory/threads/:threadId/transfer endpoint that allows changing the resourceId when called from a trusted server context (i.e., when MASTRA_RESOURCE_ID_KEY is not set in the request context, indicating a privileged/service call rather than a user-scoped one).

### Component

Integrations

### Alternatives Considered

We're currently working around this by using POST /memory/threads (`createMemoryThread`) with the existing threadId, which performs an upsert via ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE at the storage layer, bypassing the ownership check. See example code below:


```

async updateThreadResourceId(
    threadId: string,
    newResourceId: string,
    metadataUpdates?: Record<string, unknown>,
    agentId = 'fergusChatAgent',
  ): Promise<void> {
    try {
      const client = this.getMastraClient();
      const thread = client.getMemoryThread({ threadId, agentId });
      const threadDetails = await thread.get();
      await client.createMemoryThread({
        threadId,
        agentId,
        resourceId: newResourceId,
        title: threadDetails.title || '',
        metadata: {
          ...threadDetails.metadata,
          ...metadataUpdates,
        },
      });
    } catch (error) {
      this.logger.error('Error updating thread resource ID', {
        error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error),
        threadId,
        newResourceId,
      });
      throw error;
    }
  }

```

### Example Use Case

We have a use case where a server-side operation needs to transfer a thread from one resource to another (moving a user's private thread into a shared workspace). Our backend has already authorised the operation via its own permission checks before making the Mastra API call.


### Additional Context

