### Problem Statement

Currently, each tool or workflow in the system requires manual imports for shared dependencies such as API clients, singletons, and utility instances.

This approach creates several issues:

Duplication: Every tool or workflow must re-import the same dependencies.

Tight coupling: Changes in dependency imports require updates across multiple files.

Reduced clarity: It’s not always clear which global configurations or clients are available in each tool’s execution context.

Difficult scaling: As the system grows (e.g., new clients, agents, or services), maintenance becomes cumbersome.

Harder Testing: Harder to mock

### Proposed Solution

Introduce a centralized dependency injection container via the Mastra class that manages and provides access to shared resources (clients, singletons, agents, etc.).

## Design Goals

Centralize configuration and dependencies.

Make shared resources easily accessible within any tool/workflow.

Improve code maintainability and readability.

Enable more flexible test setups and mocking.

## Implementation Outline

```ts
// mastra.ts
import { mySingleton, myApiClient } from "@clients";
import { myAgentOne, myAgentTwo } from "@agents";

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  config: { mySingleton, myApiClient },
  agents: { myAgentOne, myAgentTwo },
});
```

```ts
// mytool.ts
export const getEventTool = createTool({
  id: "get-event",
  description: getEventDescription,
  inputSchema: getEventSchema,

  async execute({ context, mastra }) {
    const logger = mastra?.getLogger();
    const { myApiClient } = mastra?.getConfig() ?? {};

    logger?.info("Getting event with ID:", context.eventId);
    await myApiClient.fetchEvent(context.eventId);
  },
});
```

### Component

Other

### Alternatives Considered

Currently I'm manually importing in each tool.

### Example Use Case

```ts
// mastra.ts
import { myApiClient } from "@clients";
import { myAgentOne } from "@agents";

export const processEvent = async (eventId) => {
  const event = await myApiClient.fetchEvent(eventId);
  return myAgentOne.analyze(event);
};

// tool.ts
export const processEventTool = createTool({
  id: "process-event",
  async execute({ context, mastra }) {
    const { myApiClient } = mastra.getConfig();
    const { myAgentOne } = mastra.getAgents();

    const event = await myApiClient.fetchEvent(context.eventId);
    return myAgentOne.analyze(event);
  },
});

```

