I don't know about Langfuse, but you can make your entire tool definition dynamic. It's just a little awkward relative to the other mastra apis.

```ts
export function getWeatherTool(runtimeContext: RuntimeContext<RC>) {
  return createTool({
    id: "weather-tool",
    description: "Fetches weather for a location",
    inputSchema: z.object({
      location: z.string(),
    }),
    outputSchema: z.object({
      weather: z.string(),
    }),
    execute: async ({ context }) => {
      const { location } = context;

      const response = await fetch(`https://wttr.in/${location}?format=3`);
      const weather = await response.text();

      return { weather };
    }, 
}
```

Then, if your agent

```ts
import { openai } from "@ai-sdk/openai";
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";
import { weatherTool } from "../tools/weather-tool";

export const weatherAgent = new Agent({
  name: "weather-agent",
  instructions: `
      You are a helpful weather assistant.
      Use the weatherTool to fetch current weather data.`,
  model: openai("gpt-4o-mini"),
  tools: async ({ runtimeContext }: { runtimeContext: RuntimeContext<RC> }) => {
    return { weatherTool: getWeatherTool(runtimeContext) }
  }
});
```

This way your tools are initialized at runtime, and you can do whatever runtime-dependant modifications you need.

